Sample_treatment_protocol_ch1: Daily gavage treatment with 10mg/kg enzalutamide was initiated on the day of injection. Once tumors were palpable, tumor size was measured weekly by tumor measuring system Peira TM900 (Peira bvba, Belgium).
Sample_growth_protocol_ch1: LNCaP/AR cell line was generated and maintained as previously described (Chen et al 2003). Cells were cultured at 37° C (5% CO2) in high-glucose RPMI medium supplemented with 10% fetal bovine serum (FBS), 1% HEPES, 1% Sodium Pyruvate, 1% penicillin-streptomycin and 1% L-Glutamine. In vivo xenograft experiments were done by subcutaneous injection of 2 × 106 LNCaP/AR cells (100 μl in 50% Matrigel [BD Biosciences, San Jose, CA] and 50% growth media) into the flanks of castrated male SCID mice.
Sample_extract_protocol_ch1: Resistant LNCaP/AR xenograft tumors were harvested and the genomic DNA was isolated by two rounds of phenol extraction using PhaseLock tubes (5prime) followed by isopropanol precipitation., All genomic DNAs from tumors, plasmid or pregraft cells were PCR amplified using a protocol previously described (Zuber NBT 2011). Libraries were analyzed on an Illumina HiSeq 2500 and 18 nucleotides of the guide strand were sequenced using a custom primer as previously described (Zuber Nature 2011).
Sample_data_processing: Transform files from Fastq to Fasta (galaxy), Clip sequences at TACATC (galaxy), Filter sequences by length (22bp, galaxy), Reverse-complement (galaxy), Collapse sequences to number of reads (galaxy), Align with shRNA guide sequences (use join from Galaxy), Supplementary_files_format_and_content:, Fasta to tabular (galaxy).  For each shRNA and condition, the number of matching reads was normalized to the total number of library-specific reads per lane (10 million total reads per pool) and used for further analysis, which were reported in the processed data column as normalized count.
prostate_cancer_human_deletome.txt: A tab-delimted file containing a pooled shRNA library targeting genes most frequently deleted in primary or metastatic prostate cancer, annotated from a survey of six prostate cancer genomic datasets. (Barbieri et al., 2012; Grasso et al., 2013; Holcomb et al., 2009; Kim et al., 2007; Network, 2015; Taylor et al., 2010).
RIGER data matrix of tumor sequencing re: As requested by reviewers, a probabilistic ranking algorithm (used for in vitro screens (RIGER) to our in vivo screen) was adapted to identify true hits. However, because in vivo library screening is noisier than in vitro library screening and there are clearly stochastic effects, tumors were collected on week 16 before control tumors arise, resulting in the collection of very different numbers of resistant tumors from each pool. Thus, this data was not directly used as a probabilistic matrix, which would require the same number of repeats an in vitro library. To use a probabilistic ranking algorithm such as RIGER, the hairpin reads (in the tumors which did not score by week 16) was records as "0" because they failed to enriched quicker than the stochastic enriched hairpins, in order to have a working matrix for a probabilistic statistic model. This file is the data matrix of tumor reads ready to use by RIGER-E, which has 14 data columns including 13 (reads in tumors, maxi tumor number is 13) + 1 (reads in plasmid).

RIGER data matrix of tumor sequencing re: As requested by reviewers, a probabilistic ranking algorithm (used for in vitro screens (RIGER) to our in vivo screen) was adapted to identify true hits. However, because in vivo library screening is noisier than in vitro library screening and there are clearly stochastic effects, tumors were collected on week 16 before control tumors arise, resulting in the collection of very different numbers of resistant tumors from each pool. Thus, this data was not directly used as a probabilistic matrix, which would require the same number of repeats an in vitro library. To use a probabilistic ranking algorithm such as RIGER, the hairpin reads (in the tumors which did not score by week 16) was records as "0" because they failed to enriched quicker than the stochastic enriched hairpins, in order to have a working matrix for a probabilistic statistic model. This file is the data matrix of tumor reads ready to use by RIGER-E, which has 14 data columns including 13 (reads in tumors, maxi tumor number is 13) + 1 (reads in plasmid).

Sample_treatment_protocol_ch1: Daily gavage treatment with 10mg/kg enzalutamide was initiated on the day of injection. Once tumors were palpable, tumor size was measured weekly by tumor measuring system Peira TM900 (Peira bvba, Belgium).
Sample_growth_protocol_ch1: LNCaP/AR cell line was generated and maintained as previously described (Chen et al 2003). Cells were cultured at 37° C (5% CO2) in high-glucose RPMI medium supplemented with 10% fetal bovine serum (FBS), 1% HEPES, 1% Sodium Pyruvate, 1% penicillin-streptomycin and 1% L-Glutamine. In vivo xenograft experiments were done by subcutaneous injection of 2 × 106 LNCaP/AR cells (100 μl in 50% Matrigel [BD Biosciences, San Jose, CA] and 50% growth media) into the flanks of castrated male SCID mice.
Sample_extract_protocol_ch1: Resistant LNCaP/AR xenograft tumors were harvested and the genomic DNA was isolated by two rounds of phenol extraction using PhaseLock tubes (5prime) followed by isopropanol precipitation., All genomic DNAs from tumors, plasmid or pregraft cells were PCR amplified using a protocol previously described (Zuber NBT 2011). Libraries were analyzed on an Illumina HiSeq 2500 and 18 nucleotides of the guide strand were sequenced using a custom primer as previously described (Zuber Nature 2011).
Sample_data_processing: Transform files from Fastq to Fasta (galaxy), Clip sequences at TACATC (galaxy), Filter sequences by length (22bp, galaxy), Reverse-complement (galaxy), Collapse sequences to number of reads (galaxy), Align with shRNA guide sequences (use join from Galaxy), Supplementary_files_format_and_content:, Fasta to tabular (galaxy).  For each shRNA and condition, the number of matching reads was normalized to the total number of library-specific reads per lane (10 million total reads per pool) and used for further analysis, which were reported in the processed data column as normalized count.

In vivo xenograft experiments were done by subcutaneous injection of 2 × 106 LNCaP/AR cells (100 μl in 50% Matrigel [BD Biosciences, San Jose, CA] and 50% growth media) into the flanks of castrated male SCID mice.
Sample_extract_protocol_ch1: Resistant LNCaP/AR xenograft tumors were harvested and the genomic DNA was isolated by two rounds of phenol extraction using PhaseLock tubes (5prime) followed by isopropanol precipitation., All genomic DNAs from tumors, plasmid or pregraft cells were PCR amplified using a protocol previously described (Zuber NBT 2011). Libraries were analyzed on an Illumina HiSeq 2500 and 18 nucleotides of the guide strand were sequenced using a custom primer as previously described (Zuber Nature 2011).
Sample_data_processing: Transform files from Fastq to Fasta (galaxy), Clip sequences at TACATC (galaxy), Filter sequences by length (22bp, galaxy), Reverse-complement (galaxy), Collapse sequences to number of reads (galaxy), Align with shRNA guide sequences (use join from Galaxy), Supplementary_files_format_and_content:, Fasta to tabular (galaxy).  For each shRNA and condition, the number of matching reads was normalized to the total number of library-specific reads per lane (10 million total reads per pool) and used for further analysis, which were reported in the processed data column as normalized count.
prostate_cancer_human_deletome.txt: A tab-delimted file containing a pooled shRNA library targeting genes most frequently deleted in primary or metastatic prostate cancer, annotated from a survey of six prostate cancer genomic datasets. (Barbieri et al., 2012; Grasso et al., 2013; Holcomb et al., 2009; Kim et al., 2007; Network, 2015; Taylor et al., 2010).
RIGER data matrix of tumor sequencing re: As requested by reviewers, a probabilistic ranking algorithm (used for in vitro screens (RIGER) to our in vivo screen) was adapted to identify true hits. However, because in vivo library screening is noisier than in vitro library screening and there are clearly stochastic effects, tumors were collected on week 16 before control tumors arise, resulting in the collection of very different numbers of resistant tumors from each pool. Thus, this data was not directly used as a probabilistic matrix, which would require the same number of repeats an in vitro library. To use a probabilistic ranking algorithm such as RIGER, the hairpin reads (in the tumors which did not score by week 16) was records as "0" because they failed to enriched quicker than the stochastic enriched hairpins, in order to have a working matrix for a probabilistic statistic model. This file is the data matrix of tumor reads ready to use by RIGER-E, which has 14 data columns including 13 (reads in tumors, maxi tumor number is 13) + 1 (reads in plasmid).

Sample_data_processing: Transform files from Fastq to Fasta (galaxy), Clip sequences at TACATC (galaxy), Filter sequences by length (22bp, galaxy), Reverse-complement (galaxy), Collapse sequences to number of reads (galaxy), Align with shRNA guide sequences (use join from Galaxy), Supplementary_files_format_and_content:, Fasta to tabular (galaxy).  For each shRNA and condition, the number of matching reads was normalized to the total number of library-specific reads per lane (10 million total reads per pool) and used for further analysis, which were reported in the processed data column as normalized count.
prostate_cancer_human_deletome.txt: A tab-delimted file containing a pooled shRNA library targeting genes most frequently deleted in primary or metastatic prostate cancer, annotated from a survey of six prostate cancer genomic datasets. (Barbieri et al., 2012; Grasso et al., 2013; Holcomb et al., 2009; Kim et al., 2007; Network, 2015; Taylor et al., 2010).
RIGER data matrix of tumor sequencing re: As requested by reviewers, a probabilistic ranking algorithm (used for in vitro screens (RIGER) to our in vivo screen) was adapted to identify true hits. However, because in vivo library screening is noisier than in vitro library screening and there are clearly stochastic effects, tumors were collected on week 16 before control tumors arise, resulting in the collection of very different numbers of resistant tumors from each pool. Thus, this data was not directly used as a probabilistic matrix, which would require the same number of repeats an in vitro library. To use a probabilistic ranking algorithm such as RIGER, the hairpin reads (in the tumors which did not score by week 16) was records as "0" because they failed to enriched quicker than the stochastic enriched hairpins, in order to have a working matrix for a probabilistic statistic model. This file is the data matrix of tumor reads ready to use by RIGER-E, which has 14 data columns including 13 (reads in tumors, maxi tumor number is 13) + 1 (reads in plasmid).

Sample_treatment_protocol_ch1: Daily gavage treatment with 10mg/kg enzalutamide was initiated on the day of injection. Once tumors were palpable, tumor size was measured weekly by tumor measuring system Peira TM900 (Peira bvba, Belgium).
Sample_growth_protocol_ch1: LNCaP/AR cell line was generated and maintained as previously described (Chen et al 2003). Cells were cultured at 37° C (5% CO2) in high-glucose RPMI medium supplemented with 10% fetal bovine serum (FBS), 1% HEPES, 1% Sodium Pyruvate, 1% penicillin-streptomycin and 1% L-Glutamine. In vivo xenograft experiments were done by subcutaneous injection of 2 × 106 LNCaP/AR cells (100 μl in 50% Matrigel [BD Biosciences, San Jose, CA] and 50% growth media) into the flanks of castrated male SCID mice.
